	GETSNDPLAYER
	if (RESULT = "") then say "No sound file player defined"
	else say "Sound file player path/name = " RESULT
@ENDNODE

##
## "GETPERSLABEL"
##

@NODE getperslabel "GETPERSLABEL"
GETPERSLABEL command:
This command is no longer supported.

Label 1 will always return "Occupation".
Label 2 will always return "Comments".
Label 3 will always return "References".
@ENDNODE

##
## "GETFAMLABEL"
##

@NODE getfamlabel "GETFAMLABEL"
GETFAMLABEL command:
This command is no longer supported.

Label 1 will always return "Celebrant".
Label 2 will always return "Comments".
@ENDNODE

##
## "PUTPERSLABEL"
##

@NODE putperslabel "PUTPERSLABEL"
PUTPERSLABEL command:
This command is no longer supported, and will always return a value
of 1 (TRUE) signifying success.
@ENDNODE

##
## "PUTFAMLABEL"
##

@NODE putfamlabel "PUTFAMLABEL"
PUTFAMLABEL command:
This command is no longer supported, and will always return a value
of 1 (TRUE) signifying success.
@ENDNODE

##
## "REQUESTPERSON"
##

@NODE requestperson "REQUESTPERSON"
REQUESTPERSON command:			(V5)

Raises a "person" requester on the Scion screen (in the top left-hand
corner, if possible) and returns the IRN of the person selected from
the list (or zero for none - eg cancel).

Note that if Scion is unable to display the requester on the visible
area of the screen (might have been a large auto-scrolling screen),
it will do it's best to display the requester where it is visible
(usually in the centre of the screen).

	SYNTAX: REQUESTPERSON

	result: the IRN of the person selected from the list (or zero
	        for none - eg cancel)

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	REQUESTPERSON
	if (RESULT = 0) then say "Nobody selected"
	else say "Selected person = " RESULT
@ENDNODE

##
## "REQUESTFAMILY"
##

@NODE requestfamily "REQUESTFAMILY"
REQUESTFAMILY command:			(V5)

Raises a "family" requester on the Scion screen (in the top left-hand
corner, if possible) and returns the FGRN of the family selected from
the list (or zero for none - eg cancel).

Note that if Scion is unable to display the requester on the visible
area of the screen (might have been a large auto-scrolling screen),
it will do it's best to display the requester where it is visible
(usually in the centre of the screen).

	SYNTAX: REQUESTFAMILY

	result: the FGRN of the family selected from the list (or zero
	        for none - eg cancel)

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	REQUESTFAMILY
	if (RESULT = 0) then say "No family selected"
	else say "Selected family = " RESULT
@ENDNODE

##
## "REQUESTDATE"
##

@NODE requestdate "REQUESTDATE"
REQUESTDATE command:			(V5)

Raises a "date" requester on the Scion screen (in the top left-hand
corner, if possible) and returns the date entered in default Scion
"DD MMM YYYY" string format. Returns empty string if an internal error
occurs or if the user 'cancelled' out of the requester.

Note that if Scion is unable to display the requester on the visible
area of the screen (might have been a large auto-scrolling screen),
it will do it's best to display the requester where it is visible
(usually in the centre of the screen).

	SYNTAX: REQUESTDATE type

                      or

	        REQUESTDATE "title"

	where:

	In the first form of call, the numeric argument 'type' sets the
	(localised) requester title as follows:

		1 = Birth Date
		2 = Baptism Date
		3 = Death Date
		4 = Burial Date
		5 = Engagement Date
		6 = Wedding Date
		7 = Ended Date

	Any other value for 'type' sets the title to "Date"

	In the second form of call, the string argument "title"  sets the
	title of the requester to the user-supplied "title". This title
	may be truncated to fit the requester.

	result: the date entered by the user into the date requester.
	        Returns empty string if an internal error occurs or if
	        the user 'cancelled' out of the requester.

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	REQUESTDATE 3
	if (RESULT = "") then say "No death date"
	else say "Death date entered = " RESULT


	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	REQUESTDATE "Emigration Date"
	if (RESULT = "") then say "No emigration date"
	else say "Emigration date entered = " RESULT
@ENDNODE

##
## "REQUESTANCESTOR"
##

@NODE requestancestor "REQUESTANCESTOR"
REQUESTANCESTOR command:			(V5)

Raises an "ancestor" requester for the specified person on the Scion
screen (in the top left-hand corner, if possible) and returns the IRN
of the ancestor selected (or zero for none - eg cancel).

Note that if Scion is unable to display the requester on the visible
area of the screen (might have been a large auto-scrolling screen),
it will do it's best to display the requester where it is visible
(usually in the centre of the screen).

	SYNTAX: REQUESTANCESTOR irn

	where: 'irn' is the "base person" for the Ancestor List.

	result: the IRN of the person selected from the list (or zero
	        for none - eg cancel)

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	MyIRN = 5		/* Set "base" person to 5
	REQUESTANCESTOR MyIRN
	if (RESULT = 0) then say "Nobody selected"
	else say "Selected ancestor = " RESULT
@ENDNODE

##
## "REQUESTDESCENDANT"
##

@NODE requestdescendant "REQUESTDESCENDANT"
REQUESTDESCENDANT command:			(V5)

Raises an "descendant" requester for the specified person on the Scion
screen (in the top left-hand corner, if possible) and returns the IRN
of the descendant selected from the list (or zero for none - eg cancel).

Note that if Scion is unable to display the requester on the visible
area of the screen (might have been a large auto-scrolling screen),
it will do it's best to display the requester where it is visible
(usually in the centre of the screen).

	SYNTAX: REQUESTDESCENDANT irn

	where: 'irn' is the "base person" for the Descendant List.

	result: the IRN of the person selected from the list (or zero
	        for none - eg cancel)

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	MyIRN = 5		/* Set "base" person to 5
	REQUESTDESCENDANT MyIRN
	if (RESULT = 0) then say "Nobody selected"
	else say "Selected descendant = " RESULT
@ENDNODE

##
## "GETRELATION"
##

@NODE getrelation "GETRELATION"
GETRELATION command:			(V5)

Obtain the (possible) blood relationship between two people.

	SYNTAX: GETRELATION this_irn relative_irn

	where: 'this_irn' is the record number of the 'base' person you
	                  want to find the relative of

               'relative_irn' is the record number of the possible
	                  blood relation to 'this_irn'

	result: the blood relationship of 'relative_irn' with respect to
                'this_irn'.

                Other possible return strings are -

                  -  "Same person selected" (this_irn = relative_irn)
                  -  "Not a blood relative"
		  -  "" (Empty string if either person doesn't exist)

                Refer to the "Scion.Guide" help file for further details
		on possible relationship strings returned.

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	MyIRN = 5		/* Set "base" person to 5
	PossibleIRN = 42	/* Set possible relative to 42 */
	GETRELATION MyIRN PossibleIRN
	say "Relationship of person" PossibleIRN "to" MyIRN "is" RESULT

For example, if 'MyIRN' is YOUR record number, and 'PossibleIRN' is the
record number of your great grandfather, then the above code will display
the answer "Relationship of person 42 to 5 is Great Grandfather".

@ENDNODE

##
## "LASTSAVEDDATE"
##

@NODE lastsaveddate "LASTSAVEDDATE"
LASTSAVEDDATE command:			(V5)

Obtain the date that the database was last saved.

	SYNTAX: LASTSAVEDDATE

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	LASTSAVEDDATE
	say "Database was last saved on " RESULT
@ENDNODE

##
## "GETENDINGSTR"
##

@NODE getendingstr "GETENDINGSTR"
GETENDINGSTR command:			(V5)

Obtain the string for the "ending reason" of the specified marriage.
For example, this call will return the localised strings "Divorce",
"Separation", etc.

This is an "enhanced" version of the old GETENDING which simply returned
an index.

	SYNTAX:	GETENDINGSTR CurrentFGRN

	where: 'CurrentFGRN' is the FGRN of the family
	       of interest in the Scion database

	The result is returned in the ARexx variable RESULT.

	See also @{" GETENDING " LINK GETENDING}

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	MyFGRN = 5		/* Set MyFGRN to family 5 */
	GETENDINGSTR MyFGRN	/* Issue command to Scion Genealogist */
	Say "End reason string:" RESULT
@ENDNODE

##
## "GETPREPARER"
##

@NODE getpreparer "GETPREPARER"
GETPREPARER command:			(V5)

Obtain the preparer's name and address.

	SYNTAX: GETPREPARER

	Note that the name and address returned	is "multi-line" with each
	line separated by a '$' character.  Each line of the name/address
	can be extracted using the ARexx "PARSE VAR" command.

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	GETPREPARER
	prep_addr = RESULT
	PARSE VAR prep_addr p_name '$' addr1 '$' addr2 '$'
	say "Preparer's name:" p_name

	See also @{" GETBRKCHAR " LINK getbrkchar} and @{" PUTBRKCHAR " LINK putbrkchar}
@ENDNODE

##
## "GETPREPPHONE"
##

@NODE getprepphone "GETPREPPHONE"
GETPREPPHONE command:			(V5)

Obtain the preparer's phone number.

	SYNTAX: GETPREPPHONE

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	GETPREPPHONE
	say "Preparer's phone number = " RESULT
@ENDNODE

##
## "PUTPREPARER"
##

@NODE putpreparer "PUTPREPARER"
PUTPREPARER command:			(V5)

Set the preparer's name and address.

	SYNTAX: PUTPREPARER "name and address string"

	where: "name and address string" is the name and address of the
	       preparer of the database information.

	NOTE: The name and address string is a "multi-line" string.
	      To separate each line of the name and address, use the
	      '$' character. For example,

	      to set the name and address -
		  John Smith
		  123 Any Street
		  Sometown
		  NEW ZEALND

	      then enter this as -
	          "John Smith$123 Any Street$Sometown$NEW ZEALND"

	Do not use more than 4 "lines" as Scion is unable to display more.

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	PUTPREPARER "John Smith$123 Any Street$Sometown$NEW ZEALND"

	See also @{" GETBRKCHAR " LINK getbrkchar} and @{" PUTBRKCHAR " LINK putbrkchar}
@ENDNODE

##
## "PUTPREPPHONE"
##

@NODE putprepphone "PUTPREPPHONE"
PUTPREPPHONE command:			(V5)

Set the preparer's telephone number.

	SYNTAX: PUTPREPPHONE "phone number"

	where: "phone number" is the telephone number of the preparer
	       of the database information.

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	PUTPREPPHONE "+1 +555 123-4567"
@ENDNODE

##
## "GETBRKCHAR"
##

@NODE getbrkchar "GETBRKCHAR"
GETBRKCHAR command:			(V5)

Obtain the current "line-break" character(s) for the multi-line name
and address strings. Default value is "$".

	SYNTAX: GETBRKCHAR

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	GETBRKCHAR
	say "Current break character is " RESULT

	See also @{" PUTBRKCHAR " LINK putbrkchar}
@ENDNODE

##
## "PUTBRKCHAR"
##

@NODE putbrkchar "PUTBRKCHAR"
PUTBRKCHAR command:			(V5)

Set the current "line-break" character(s) for multi-line name and
address strings to the character(s) "chars".

	SYNTAX: PUTBRKCHAR "chars"

	where: "chars" is the new "line-break" character(s) for
	       multi-line name and address strings. For	example,
	       to change the default '$' separator to '%%', issue the
	       command PUTBRKCHAR "%%". Only the first two "break"
	       characters are recognised. That is, "chars" can be
	       1 or 2 characters.

	NOTE: If you want to assure that the specified characters won't
	appear in an address ('$' is already highly unlikely), you could
	use one or two of the special characters such as ż, ®, «, ╝, Į, Š,
	▒, etc in addition to making the 'break' 2 characters.

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */

	PUTBRKCHAR "%%"	/* Change "break" character from '$' to '%%' */
	GETBRKCHAR
	brk_char = RESULT

	PUTPREPARER "John Smith"brk_char"123 Some Street"brk_char"ThisTown"brk_char"My Country"

	GETPREPARER
	preparer = RESULT
	PARSE VAR preparer p_name (brk_char) p_adr1 (brk_char) p_adr2 (brk_char) p_adr3
	say "Preparer's name " p_name
	say "Preparer's adr1 " p_adr1
	say "Preparer's adr2 " p_adr2
	say "Preparer's adr3 " p_adr3

	See also @{" GETBRKCHAR " LINK getbrkchar}
@ENDNODE

##
## "DELETEPERSON"
##

@NODE deleteperson "DELETEPERSON"
DELETEPERSON command:			(V5)

Deletes the record of the specified person. Any marriages of that
person will also be deleted.

	Syntax: DELETEPERSON irn

	where: 'irn' is the record number of the person to delete from
	       the database

	No return value.

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	MyIRN = 5		/* Set MyIRN to person 5 */
	DELETEPERSON MyIRN
@ENDNODE

##
## "GETPERSADDR"
##

@NODE getpersaddr "GETPERSADDR"
GETPERSADDR command:			(V5)

Obtain the address for the specified person.

	Syntax: GETPERSADDR irn

	where: 'irn' is the record number to obtain the address of.

	Note that the address returned is "multi-line" with each line
	separated by a '$' character. Each line of the address can be
	extracted using the ARexx "PARSE VAR" command.

EXAMPLE USAGE:
	MyPort = "SCIONGEN"	/* Point at Scion Genealogist port */
	Address value MyPort	/* Change ARexx address to that port */
	GETPERSADDR 42
	pers_addr = RESULT
	PARSE VAR pers_addr line_1 '$' line_2 '$' line_3 '$'
	say "First line of person 42's address:" line_1

	See also @{" GETBRKCHAR " LINK getbrkchar} and @{" PUTBRKCHAR " LINK putbrkchar}
@ENDNODE

